entry.infobox: When a means its or his, it causes a lenition on the noun that follows it. It doesn't cause any changes on nouns that begin with vowels.
When a means her, it attaches a h to the noun that follows it if it starts with a vowel. It doesn't cause any mutations on nouns that begin with consonants.
When a means their, it causes an ecplisis on the noun that follows it.
When a verbal noun has a direct object, then the direct object precedes the verbal noun and is separated from it by a.

entry.infobox: In spoken Irish the language is called Gaeilg in Ulster, Gaeilge in Connacht and Gaelainn in Munster. It is the Connacht version which is most widely known, and usually adopted by learners of Irish as the name of the language.

To say that something is in Irish we have two options: i nGaeilge (literally 'in Irish') and as Gaeilge (literally 'out of Irish'). The former is used more widely. The latter is only used in Munster dialects and only refers to spoken language: labhraítear as Gaeilge one speaks 'out of Irish' but scríobhtar i nGaeilge one writes 'in Irish'.

entry.infobox: Use this word carefully. Not everybody who speaks Irish is a Gaeilgeoir or wants to be described as one. English speakers sometimes use the word as a derogatory reference to a bothersome person who insists on speaking Irish when it's not convenient, while native Irish speakers from the Gaeltacht are more likely to apply the term to Irish learners from the cities rather than to themselves. If you want to refer to an Irish speaker neutrally, say cainteoir Gaeilge Irish speaker, duine le Gaeilge somebody with Irish or duine a bhfuil Gaeilge aige somebody who speaks Irish.

In the Republic of Ireland, some geographical areas are officially designated as a Gaeltacht. Road signage in these areas is in Irish only (while it is bilingual in the rest of the country), local schools are expected to function exclusively through Irish, and so on. Apart from this legal sense, some people use the word Gaeltacht more loosely to refer to any Irish-speaking area, regardless of its official status. The Gaelic-speaking areas of Scotland are also called a Gaeltacht. While the word almost always refers to a place or geographical area, in some older usage it is a collective term for the community of Irish-speaking people everywhere.

entry.infobox: Gnéas refers to the fact of being physically fear man or bean woman. For gender as a social construct or as a grammatical category, see inscne.
Contrary to popular usage among non-native speakers of Irish, gnéas does not mean sex in the sense of intercouse, having sex. For this use collaíocht, craiceann or leathar.

entry.infobox: A Gael is somebody who is not only Irish (Éireannach) but also is rooted in native Gaelic culture. Irish speakers sometimes describes themselves as Gaeil.

The word Gall can have two meanings. It can refer to a foreigner, especially from countries that have at some stage invaded Ireland. It is probably the word the Irish once used to refer to Anglo-Normal invaders who had originated from Gaul (= Nothern France). It can also refer to a person who is from Ireland but is not rooted in Ireland's native Gaelic culture and identifies more closely with the Anglo-Irish tradition. It is not a very polite word but it can be used jokingly.
Pota Focal is a famous online Irish dictonary and, in our view, the best.

entry.infobox: The adjective sean behaves like a prefix when it modifies a noun attributively: an old house is always seanteach, never teach sean. However, when sean itself is modified by something, then it acts like a normal adjective: teach an-sean a very old house, teach níos sine an older house. Also, when sean is being used predicatively, it is again a normal adjective: tá an teach sean the house is old*.
